04742nam a22006735i 9780674059634DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221992mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740596347 a10.4159/97806740596342doi  a(DE-B1597)626071  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHD9141.9.P47bP75 1992 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a382/.41371/09422201 aPrice, Jacob M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerry of London :bA Family and a Firm on the Seaborne Frontier, 1615–1753 /cJacob M. Price. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (105 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHarvard Historical Studies ;v11100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Names -- tIntroduction -- tPart I The Rise of the House of Perry, 1615–1721 -- t1 / The Early Perrys and Their Wanderings -- t2 / The Emergence of Perry & Lane -- t3 / The Business of the Perry Firm -- t4 / The Public Role of Micaiah Perry I -- tPart II The Fall of the House of Perry, 1721–1753 -- t5 / The Challenge of the Third Generation -- t6 / The Perils of Politics -- t7 / The Family after the Fall -- tConclusion: Choosing a Frame for the Picture -- tAbbreviations -- tAppendix A Draft service agreement (1684) between a London merchant (William Paggen) and his prospective Virginia factor (John Hardman) -- tAppendix B Goods exported by Perry, Lane & Co. to Virginia and Maryland in year ending Lady Day 1697/8 -- tAppendix C The Hutchinson Connection -- tAppendix D The Early Perys and Perrys: Some Problems -- tSelected Bibliography -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Establishment of English colonies in North America and the West Indies in the seventeenth century opened new opportunities for trade. Conspicuous among the families who used these opportunities to gain mercantile and social importance was the Perry family of Devon, who created Perry and Lane, by the end of the century the most important London firm trading to the Chesapeake and other parts of North America. Jacob Price traces the family from Devon to Spain, Ireland, Scotland, the Chesapeake, New England, and London. He describes their relationships with Chesapeake society, from the Byrds and Carters to humble planters. In London, the firm’s patronage gave the family high standing among fellow businessmen, a position the founder’s grandson utilized to become a member of Parliament and Lord Mayor of London. In the end, the grandson’s political success as an antiministerialist brought the family the enmity of the prime minister, Sir Robert Walpole, and contributed to the downfall of their firm. The Perrys’ story reveals the interrelatedness of social, commercial, and political history. It offers an important contribution to our understanding of the nature of the Chesapeake trade and the forces shaping the success and failure of English mercantile enterprise in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTobacco industryzGreat BritainxColoniesxHistory. 0aTobacco industryzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aTobacco industryzVirginiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067405963440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674059634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674059634/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGB